stanford law hosts opinions from china's top court stanford law school stanford law school search utility navigation test directory news center library events publications contact & maps information for prospective students alumni employers current students faculty & staff news center stanford law hosts opinions from china's top court go back publication date january 10 2012 source thomson reuters news & insight among the areas of the law that summary judgments confesses to knowing absolutely nothing about the workings of china's supreme court is way up there until now stanford law school announced on monday that it is launching a website of the guiding cases issued by china's supreme people's court while these cases aren t precedential in the western common law sense they are subject to a november 2010 chinese rule to be referred to with guidance by courts throughout the country in other words china's legal system is evolving before our very eyes and stanford's new website which lists the first of these four opinions is there to capture that evolution all opinions will be translated into english to facilitate an ongoing dialogue about the development of chinese law lawyers professors and other interested parties will be invited to comment on the implications of the cases full story related faculty none related none cloudy 51 f 2012 stanford university system requirements help virtual tour
